---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="NotebookLM Multimedia & Visualization"
  description="From Audio Overviews and Video Overviews to Slides and Infographics, NotebookLM can reshape the same material into audio, video, visual, and shareable formats."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container nb-media">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Multimedia &amp; Visualization: Turning material into something you can listen to, watch, and share</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          Once your sources are in NotebookLM, organizing the material does not have to stay in chat form.
          On top of text summaries, NotebookLM can also turn content into
          <strong>audio, video, slides, and visual imagery</strong> —
          giving you different ways to re-understand the same material. Most of this output is
          generated and managed inside the <strong>Studio panel</strong> on the right of your notebook.
        </p>
        <p class="platform-note">
          <span class="platform-note__label">Platform note</span>
          Mobile support for these features <strong>is not fully uniform</strong>; some tools may be limited or look slightly different from the web UI.
          Also, <strong>Slides and Infographics are currently marked by Google as available only to users 18 and older</strong>.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section 1: Four tools overview -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Four output formats, four kinds of situations</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The four tools each suit a different situation: when you don't have time to sit and read, use audio;
        when you want the content to be easier to see, use video; when you need to present or share the result,
        use slides; when you want to grasp the gist in one glance, use a single image.
      </p>

      <div class="feature-grid feature-grid--four">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">01</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Audio Overview</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">A version you can listen to</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            Turns your sources into <strong>an audio track</strong> — good for commutes,
            pre-meeting warm-ups, or building a first sense of the material before reading.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">02</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Video Overview</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">An easier-to-follow explainer</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            Turns the main points into <strong>an AI-narrated video</strong>, adding visuals and voiceover
            on top of the text — useful for concept intros, topic overviews, and pre-class prep.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">03</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Slide Deck</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">A presentable, editable deck</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            Generates <strong>a first-pass deck</strong> from your sources — helpful for topic overviews,
            internal briefings, event recaps, teaching notes, and case walkthroughs.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="feature-card">
          <p class="feature-index">04</p>
          <h3 class="feature-title">Infographic</h3>
          <p class="feature-alias">The gist in one image</p>
          <p class="feature-desc">
            Shapes the main ideas, data, or relationships into <strong>a single-page visual</strong>,
            so readers can grasp the main points or see how things connect at a glance.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2: Audio Overviews -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Audio Overview: Turning text into a version you can listen to</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Audio Overviews are a good fit for the <strong>"absorb the material quickly first"</strong> situation.
        NotebookLM generates an audio segment based on your uploaded sources to walk you through the main points.
        The default format is "Deep Dive" — two AI hosts unpacking the topic in conversation;
        if you want something faster, "Brief" has a single speaker cover the main points in about two minutes.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">Available formats:</p>
      <div class="source-grid">
        <span class="source-chip">Deep Dive (two-host conversation)</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Brief (single speaker, ~2 min)</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Critique (constructive feedback)</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Debate (multiple angles)</span>
      </div>

      <section class="concept-card">
        <p class="concept-card__label">What you can adjust before generating</p>
        <p class="concept-card__body">
          In a notebook, pick <strong>"Audio Overview"</strong> in the Studio panel — generation starts in the background,
          and you can keep working in NotebookLM meanwhile (checking citations, searching the sources, asking more questions).
          Before generating you can set:
        </p>
        <ul class="concept-card__list">
          <li><strong>Format</strong> (Deep Dive / Brief / Critique / Debate)</li>
          <li><strong>Output language</strong></li>
          <li><strong>A prompt</strong> to tell it what to focus on</li>
          <li><strong>Length</strong> (Short / Default / Long)</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Audio Overviews are most useful when you <strong>don't have time to sit down and read</strong> —
        listening through the key points on a commute, a quick warm-up before a meeting,
        or building a first sense of the material before you actually read it.
      </p>

      <section class="caution-card">
        <p class="caution-card__label">⚠️ A quick note</p>
        <ul class="caution-card__numbered">
          <li>
            <strong>Both the voice and the content are AI-generated</strong> — so there may be inaccuracies,
            slightly unnatural speech, or the occasional audio stutter.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Interactive mode is currently English-only</strong> — you can download and share Audio Overviews,
            but people who open your shared link cannot keep talking to the hosts the way you could in your own interactive session.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: Video Overviews -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Video Overview: Shaping the main points into an easier-to-watch explainer</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If Audio Overviews are about <strong>"understanding by listening,"</strong> Video Overviews lean more toward
        <strong>"understanding by watching."</strong>
        NotebookLM turns the sources in your notebook into an AI-narrated video, adding visuals and voiceover
        on top of what would otherwise be text. This kind of video is a good fit for concept explanations,
        topic overviews, pre-class prep, warm-ups, or situations where you want to get a sense of direction quickly.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">Available video formats:</p>
      <div class="source-grid">
        <span class="source-chip">Explainer (full walkthrough)</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Brief (short highlights)</span>
        <span class="source-chip">Cinematic (Ultra only, 18+, English)</span>
      </div>

      <section class="concept-card">
        <p class="concept-card__label">Beyond format, you can also fine-tune</p>
        <ul class="concept-card__list">
          <li><strong>Narration language</strong> — Google supports 80+ languages, so you can produce a first-pass in different languages.</li>
          <li><strong>Visual style</strong> — decide the overall look of the video.</li>
          <li><strong>A prompt</strong> — tell it which topics or sources to focus on.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        A Video Overview is not just text moved onto a screen — it is meant to be a version that is
        <strong>easier to watch and follow</strong>. For people who would rather not work through long reading,
        or when you want to turn material into something easier to share, a video tends to be more inviting than a plain summary.
      </p>

      <section class="caution-card">
        <p class="caution-card__label">⚠️ A quick note</p>
        <ul class="caution-card__numbered">
          <li>
            <strong>Generation takes patience</strong> — Google notes that video generation can sometimes take
            <strong>30 minutes or more</strong>.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Audio and visuals are both AI-generated</strong> — there may be content errors or audio artifacts.
            Think of it as a tool that helps you produce a first visual draft, not something that will fully auto-produce a polished teaching video.
          </li>
          <li>
            Once generated, you can download the video file directly or share it so others can watch.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Slides -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Slides: Organizing material into a presentable, editable deck</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        The Slides tool fits the stage where
        <strong>"the organized result needs to be presented, shared, or shown."</strong>
        NotebookLM can generate a deck from your sources so you don't have to start from a blank canvas.
        It is well suited to pulling scattered material from several sources into a structured sequence of slides —
        for topic overviews, internal briefings, event recaps, teaching notes, or case walkthroughs.
      </p>

      <section class="concept-card">
        <p class="concept-card__label">Two main directions to choose from</p>
        <ul class="concept-card__list">
          <li>
            <strong>Detailed briefing</strong> — a thorough, information-rich version, suited to reading or sending.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Presentation slides</strong> — leaner and more visual, suited to accompanying a spoken talk.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="concept-card__footer">
          You can also set the output language, length, or add a prompt telling it about your audience, style, and priorities.
          NotebookLM lets you play the deck directly inside the interface, so you can see the overall flow and pacing.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="caution-card">
        <p class="caution-card__label">⚠️ A quick note</p>
        <ul class="caution-card__numbered">
          <li>
            <strong>Currently available to users 18 and older</strong> — the mobile version is usable,
            but may look different from the web version.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>You can't add or delete slides yet</strong> — revisions can edit existing slides,
            but the number of slides is fixed.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Revisions do not re-consult the sources</strong> — follow-up tweaks behave more like editing an existing deck,
            not like regenerating a full pass from the original material.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        It helps to think of Slides as
        <strong>"a tool that gives you a structured first draft of a deck,"</strong>
        not an AI layout tool that will never change content. For anything formal, it is still worth checking
        whether the content is accurate and whether the order makes sense.
        When you're done, NotebookLM lets you export the deck as
        <strong>PDF or PowerPoint (.pptx)</strong>,
        so further edits, on-stage playback, or separate sharing are all easy to do.
      </p>

      <!-- Section 5: Infographic -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Infographic: Condensing the main points into a single readable image</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Infographics are a good fit for situations where you want to
        <strong>"understand the main points quickly."</strong>
        NotebookLM pulls the key ideas, numbers, or relationships out of your sources and shapes them into
        a single-page visual — helping you grasp the main points, see connections across the material,
        or present hard-to-enter content in a more direct form.
      </p>

      <section class="concept-card">
        <p class="concept-card__label">There are quite a few things you can adjust</p>
        <ul class="concept-card__list">
          <li><strong>Output language</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Detail level</strong> — Concise / Standard / Detailed (beta).</li>
          <li><strong>Orientation</strong> — Landscape / Portrait / Square.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Visual style</strong> — let the system decide automatically, or steer it toward hand-drawn, playful, professional, and so on.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>A prompt</strong> — ask it to emphasize certain points, use a particular color palette,
            or center on specific numbers.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        An infographic is useful as
        <strong>"a single image that invites the reader into the topic."</strong>
        It is a good fit for concept organization, process explanations, highlighting key figures,
        or acting as a visual waypoint in a longer piece of writing. Long blocks of text do not always stick in memory,
        but a well-organized image often does. When you're done, NotebookLM lets you download infographics as
        <strong>PNG</strong>, and you can share them directly or via the whole notebook.
      </p>

      <section class="caution-card">
        <p class="caution-card__label">⚠️ A quick note</p>
        <p class="caution-card__body">
          Like the other generated outputs, infographics are not guaranteed to be entirely correct.
          Google notes that these images can contain
          <strong>visual or factual inaccuracies</strong>,
          so it's sensible to treat them as an efficient first visual pass, not as a substitute for human review.
          If you spot typos, odd wording, or characters that don't render naturally, the safest move is usually to
          <strong>adjust the prompt and regenerate</strong>, then decide whether any hand touch-ups are still needed.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Canva workaround -->
      <h3 class="detail-subheading">Touching up text: Post-processing in Canva</h3>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If only a small amount of text needs tweaking, you can import the downloaded PNG into Canva for post-processing.
        Canva supports PNG uploads; once uploaded, you can try <strong>Grab Text</strong> first —
        it extracts the text in the image into an editable layer so you can modify it directly.
        Canva positions this tool explicitly as a way to fix text in images,
        including correcting typos, updating wording, and adjusting font, size, and color.
      </p>

      <ol class="start-steps">
        <li class="start-step">
          <span class="start-step__num">A</span>
          <div class="start-step__body">
            <h4 class="start-step__title">Try Grab Text first (a Canva Pro feature)</h4>
            <p class="start-step__desc">
              After uploading the PNG, use Grab Text to extract the text into an editable layer.
              You can then fix typos, update wording, or adjust font, size, and color directly.
              This works best when the characters are clean and easy to recognize.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-step">
          <span class="start-step__num">B</span>
          <div class="start-step__body">
            <h4 class="start-step__title">When recognition isn't reliable, go manual</h4>
            <p class="start-step__desc">
              Use <strong>Magic Eraser</strong> to clear the incorrect text, or cover the original text with a same-colored block,
              then add a new text box and re-type the correct text.
              This is more hands-on, but for infographics with small text, busy backgrounds, or unusual typography,
              it tends to be easier to control.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <section class="caution-card">
        <p class="caution-card__label">⚠️ Another reminder</p>
        <p class="caution-card__body">
          This is <strong>external post-processing in Canva</strong>, not part of NotebookLM's own infographic revision flow.
          The edited file and the original notebook are not linked.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Closing -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Four outputs, four ways into the same material</h2>
      <blockquote class="pullquote pullquote--primary">
        Listen to it, watch it, present it, or see it in one glance — the same material can have four different entry points.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Audio Overviews, Video Overviews, Slides, and Infographics are not meant to replace your own understanding of the material.
        They help you reshape the same source into forms that are
        <strong>easier to absorb and easier to share</strong>.
        NotebookLM already makes it clear that this output is AI-generated and may contain mistakes,
        so the more reasonable way to use them is as
        <strong>an efficient first pass</strong> —
        and then go back to the original sources to verify, adjust, or touch up with other tools when needed.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .nb-media {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-subtitle strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .platform-note {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .platform-note__label {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-right: var(--space-2);
    padding: 0 var(--space-2);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .platform-note strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-subheading {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-8);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Feature grid (four tools overview, 2x2) */
  .feature-grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin-top: var(--space-6);
  }

  .feature-grid--four {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
  }

  .feature-card {
    position: relative;
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .feature-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
    box-shadow: 0 4px 12px var(--color-card-shadow);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .feature-index {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .feature-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-1);
  }

  .feature-alias {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-3);
    border-bottom: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
  }

  .feature-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .feature-desc strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Concept card */
  .concept-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
  }

  .concept-card__label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .concept-card__body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .concept-card__body strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .concept-card__list {
    margin: var(--space-3) 0 0;
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .concept-card__list li {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .concept-card__list strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .concept-card__footer {
    margin-top: var(--space-4);
    padding-top: var(--space-4);
    border-top: 1px dashed var(--color-border);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .concept-card__footer strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Caution card */
  .caution-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-4);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-text-secondary);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
  }

  .caution-card__label {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .caution-card__body {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
  }

  .caution-card__body strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered {
    margin: 0;
    padding-left: var(--space-5);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    counter-reset: caution;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered li {
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    padding-left: var(--space-3);
    counter-increment: caution;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered li::before {
    content: counter(caution);
    position: absolute;
    left: -1.25rem;
    top: 0;
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 1.25rem;
    height: 1.25rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    color: var(--color-bg);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .caution-card__numbered strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Source chips */
  .source-grid {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: var(--space-2);
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .source-chip {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-2) var(--space-4);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    color: var(--color-text);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: 9999px;
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  /* Pullquote */
  .pullquote {
    margin: var(--space-8) 0;
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-radius: 0 var(--border-radius) var(--border-radius) 0;
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .pullquote--primary {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    border-left-width: 4px;
  }

  /* Start steps */
  .start-steps {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-4) 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-3);
  }

  .start-step {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
